  "data": {
    "query": "ERCOT generation interconnection fees milestones fee schedule",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "ERCOT",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "c2995e81-75a7-4720-be2c-3b3782fec3d4",
        "score": 0.7784448,
        "text": "The document is an ERCOT fee schedule effective October 1, 2024. It outlines various fees related to ERCOT services, which are non-refundable unless specified by ERCOT Protocols.\n\n1. **Private Wide Area Network (WAN) Fees**:\n   - Based on actual costs for procuring, using, maintaining, and connecting to third-party networks for ERCOT WAN communications.\n   - Initial installation or reconfiguration costs capped at $7,000.\n   - Monthly network management fee capped at $450.\n\n2. **ERCOT Load Resource Registration and Generator Interconnection or Modification Fees**:\n   - $500 for registering a new Load Resource.\n   - Additional $500 if increasing MW size by more than 20% or changing registration type.\n   - Generator registration fees:\n     - $2,300 for Settlement Only Distribution Generators (SODGs).\n     - $8,000 for generators under 10 MW.\n     - $14,000 for generators 10 MW or greater.\n   - $8,000 for changing an existing SODG to a Distribution Generation Resource (DGR).\n\nThe document provides specific fee amounts and conditions for various registration and modification scenarios.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_2.jpg",
          "page_num": 2,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d1db4316-6cd7-4f00-aa3a-acaf1c0c62a1",
        "score": 0.7003486,
        "text": "The document is a fee schedule from ERCOT effective October 1, 2024. It outlines various application and inspection fees related to energy generation and transmission services. Key points include:\n\n1. **Full Interconnection Study (FIS) Application Fee**: \n   - $3,000 for new generators.\n   - $2,700 for modifications to existing generators.\n\n2. **Qualified Scheduling Entity (QSE) and Related Fees**:\n   - $500 per entity for QSE, Sub-QSE, Competitive Retailer (CR), Congestion Revenue Right (CRR) Account Holder, Independent Market Information System Registered Entity (IMRE), Resource Entity, and Transmission/Distribution Service Providers (TDSPs).\n\n3. **Counter-Party Background Check Fee**:\n   - $350 per principal.\n\n4. **Weatherization Inspection Fees**:\n   - Resource Entities and Transmission Service Providers must pay fees for weatherization inspections as per Texas Administrative Code \u00a7 25.55.\n\nThe document specifies that fees are associated with modifications based on the cumulative megawatt (MW) amount of changes submitted within the last 12 months. If modifications are less than 10 MW, the fee is $2,300; if 10 MW or greater, the fee is $14,000.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_3.jpg",
          "page_num": 3,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c9f4953b-d4cf-427b-90b5-fb5e568953d6",
        "score": 0.6437367,
        "text": "The document is a page from the 2002 Annual Report of the Market Oversight Division, focusing on the ERCOT Administration Fee and Uplift Costs. It includes a table detailing monthly costs from July 2001 to December 2002, with categories such as Balancing Energy Neutrality Adjustment, Black Start Capacity Charge, and others, culminating in a total of $396,027,458.\n\nThe text discusses \"Congestion Rights,\" which began in February 2002. These rights are financial instruments allowing market participants to hedge against congestion costs. The document explains the allocation and auctioning of Transmission Congestion Rights (TCRs) and Pre-assigned Congestion Rights (PCRs), noting that 60% of TCRs are awarded annually and 40% monthly. The total TCR auction revenue was $91.1 million, with credit payments of $22.5 million, resulting in a net revenue of $68.7 million.\n\nThe section on \"Market Issues\" addresses overscheduling and BENA (Balancing Energy Neutrality Adjustment). It highlights how the costs for relieving zonal congestion were distributed among market participants, incentivizing them to schedule generation across congested areas to receive higher payments.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2002/page_12.jpg",
          "page_num": 12,
          "title": "2002 Annual Report on The ERCOT Wholesale Market",
          "year": 2002,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "5db85b18-d957-4966-905b-4bc8062d53b4",
        "score": 0.64175165,
        "text": "The document page outlines specific fees related to ERCOT services:\n\n1. **Requests**: If a request requires ERCOT employee or contractor time, an estimate of labor costs will be provided. The requestor must approve and pay these costs before receiving the information.\n\n2. **ERCOT Training Fees**: Courses that award Continuing Education Hours (CEHs) cost $25 per North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) CEH. Examples include the Operator Training Seminar and Black Start Training.\n\n3. **Cybersecurity Monitor Fee**: This fee for non-ERCOT utilities participating in the Texas Cybersecurity Monitor Program varies annually. The current fee is available on ERCOT's website.\n\nThe document is part of the ERCOT Fee Schedule effective October 1, 2024.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_5.jpg",
          "page_num": 5,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "604622c0-b438-49d8-8d30-53eab9eec2f8",
        "score": 0.64142156,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to settlement and billing by ERCOT. Key points include:\n\n1. **Cost Evaluation and Reporting (Section 3):** \n   - Within 60 days of approving a profile segment, ERCOT evaluates submitted costs, disallowing those not meeting criteria. The remaining costs form the total reimbursable cost.\n   - ERCOT posts a report on its website summarizing allowed expenses.\n   - Market Participants can dispute ERCOT's determination within 45 days of the report posting.\n\n2. **Fee Calculation (Section 4):**\n   - If the requestor is a REP (Retail Electric Provider), the fee is calculated as FEE = $C / n.\n   - If not a REP, the fee is FEE = $C / (n + 1).\n   - Variables: \n     - $C = Total reimbursable cost\n     - n = Number of REPs subscribing to the profile segment\n\n3. **Fee Payment (Section 5):**\n   - Each subscribing REP must pay the fee to the requestor and previous REPs.\n   - As more REPs subscribe, the fee is recalculated and shared among all.\n\n4. **Assignment of ESI IDs (Section 6):**\n   - Four years after the profile segment is available, REPs can request assignment of Electric Service Identifiers without a development cost recovery fee.\n\n5. **Partial Payments by Invoice Recipients (Section 9.19):**\n   - ERCOT will attempt to collect payments from short-paying Invoice Recipients.\n   - ERCOT may draw on any pledged Financial Security if payments are not made in full.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_56.jpg",
          "page_num": 56,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "358386a7-6785-401f-bf79-ddf1ef8de19c",
        "score": 0.639619,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) regarding user fees and transmission billing determinants.\n\n1. **User Fees:**\n   - ERCOT is required to post user fees approved by the ERCOT Board on its website within two business days of any changes.\n   - Market Participants or other entities must pay these approved user fees.\n\n2. **Transmission Billing Determinant Calculation:**\n   - ERCOT provides Market Participants with necessary parameters and formulas to calculate billing charges for using Transmission or Distribution Facilities.\n   - ERCOT is not responsible for billing, collection, or disbursal of payments for transmission access service.\n\n3. **Billing Determinant Data Elements:**\n   - ERCOT calculates and provides data elements annually for Transmission Service Providers (TSPs) and Distribution Service Providers (DSPs) to use as billing determinants.\n   - Data must be provided by December 1 each year and comply with specific regulatory requirements.\n   - Key data elements include:\n     - The 4-Coincident Peak (4-CP) for each DSP and External Load Serving Entity (ELSE).\n     - The ERCOT average 4-CP.\n     - The average 4-CP for each DSP and ELSE coincident to the ERCOT average 4-CP.\n   - The ERCOT average 4-CP is the average of the coincidental MW peaks during June, July, August, and September.\n   - Coincidental MW peak is defined as the highest monthly Settlement Interval 15-minute MW peak for the entire ERCOT Transmission Grid, calculated using a specific formula involving net energy production and transfers.\n\nThe document also references updates to be made in accordance with NPRR995 and NPRR1188.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_52.jpg",
          "page_num": 52,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "92c1cccc-1205-4a0d-b089-6e6f39f48552",
        "score": 0.62273246,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"ERCOT 2014 State of the Market Report\" and discusses the average clearing prices for four ancillary services, with energy prices ranging from $25 to $60 per MWh. Ancillary service costs increased by 47% to $1.51 per MWh. \n\nThe section on \"Transmission and Congestion\" notes that congestion revenue in the ERCOT real-time market for 2014 was $708 million, a 52% increase from 2013. This rise was attributed to higher gas prices and increased congestion, particularly in the South and Houston zones. A graph illustrates the frequency of binding and active transmission constraints across different load levels from 2012 to 2014, showing an increase in constraints over time.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2014/page_16.jpg",
          "page_num": 16,
          "title": "2014 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Wholesale Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2014,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f8363d52-e903-4a17-a962-e9bb66f5f3cd",
        "score": 0.6224908,
        "text": "The document page discusses the breakdown of electricity costs in 2022 within the ERCOT market. Key points include:\n\n- Ancillary services costs were $3.29 per MWh, a 90% reduction from 2021 but more than triple the 2020 costs.\n- Uplift costs were $0.77 per MWh, significantly lower than $5.34 in 2021 and $0.94 in 2020.\n- Total uplift costs in 2022 were approximately $368 million, down from $2.1 billion in 2021, largely due to the absence of events like Winter Storm Uri.\n- Major components of uplift costs included the ERCOT System Administrative Fee ($293 million) and Emergency Response Service program costs ($36 million).\n- Real-Time Revenue Neutrality Allocation (RENA) was $43 million, a significant increase from less than $1 million in 2021.\n- A graph illustrates monthly variations in all-in electricity costs, showing peaks in summer months, with natural gas prices also charted.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2022/page_41.jpg",
          "page_num": 41,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3cbc68a7-61f1-4fb3-ae6f-2dbdf8fc4be4",
        "score": 0.6213952,
        "text": "The document provides an analysis of 2022 prices and outcomes in ERCOT's real-time energy market. It includes a table summarizing the annual aggregate costs of various ERCOT charges or payments for 2022. The table lists different cost types and their corresponding annual totals in millions of dollars. Key cost types include:\n\n- Energy: $32,225 million\n- Regulation Up: $78 million\n- Regulation Down: $28 million\n- Responsive Reserve: $383 million\n- Non-Spin: $743 million\n- Balancing Account Surplus: $299 million\n- CRR Auction Distribution: $1,098 million\n- CRR Day-Ahead Market Payment: $2,066 million\n- PTP Day-Ahead Market Charge: $1,798 million\n- PTP RT Payment: $2,162 million\n- Emergency Response Service: $36 million\n- Revenue Neutrality Uplift: $43 million\n- AS Imbalance Uplift: $6 million\n- ERCOT Fee: $239 million\n- ERO Passthrough Fee: $22 million\n- Other Load Allocation: $1 million\n\nThe analysis focuses on net charges after self-arrangement and calculates real-time energy values based on megawatts generated.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2022/page_155.jpg",
          "page_num": 155,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6e1db462-e154-4eb0-b0e8-d69c544ad22e",
        "score": 0.6210625,
        "text": "The document is an appendix from the \"2022 State of the Market Report\" focusing on the monthly aggregate costs of various ERCOT market settlement totals for 2022. It includes a table titled \"Table A2: Market at a Glance Monthly,\" which details costs in millions of dollars across different categories for each month.\n\nKey categories include:\n\n- **Energy**: Costs range from $1,053 million in January to $2,321 million in December, with a peak of $7,561 million in July.\n- **Regulation Up/Down**: Costs vary monthly, with notable peaks in July for Regulation Up ($18 million) and consistent low values for Regulation Down.\n- **Responsive Reserve**: Peaks at $91 million in July, with lower values in other months.\n- **Non-Spin**: Highest in July at $141 million.\n- **CRR Auction Distribution**: Ranges from $65 million in February to $114 million in June.\n- **Balancing Account Surplus**: Peaks at $72 million in June.\n- **CRR DAM Payment**: Highest in May at $430 million.\n- **PTP DAM/RT Payment**: Notable peaks in May ($390 million) and June ($574 million) respectively.\n- **Emergency Response Service**: Generally low, with a peak of $6 million in January.\n- **Revenue Neutrality Uplift**: Fluctuates, with negative values in March and July.\n- **AS Imbalance Uplift**: Peaks in April at $13 million, with negative values in July.\n- **ERCOT Fee**: Consistent around $17-$26 million monthly.\n- **ERO Passthrough Fee**: Steady at $2 million monthly.\n- **Firm Fuel**: Only appears in November and December.\n- **Other Load Allocation**: Minor fluctuations, with some negative values.\n\nOverall, the table provides a comprehensive monthly breakdown of costs associated with various market activities within ERCOT for 2022.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2022/page_156.jpg",
          "page_num": 156,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

