        "score": 0.72105706,
        "text": "The document is an ERCOT fee schedule effective October 1, 2024. It outlines various fees related to ERCOT services, which are non-refundable unless specified by ERCOT Protocols.\n\n1. **Private Wide Area Network (WAN) Fees**:\n   - Based on actual costs for procuring, using, maintaining, and connecting to third-party networks for ERCOT WAN communications.\n   - Initial installation or reconfiguration costs capped at $7,000.\n   - Monthly network management fee capped at $450.\n\n2. **ERCOT Load Resource Registration and Generator Interconnection or Modification Fees**:\n   - $500 for registering a new Load Resource.\n   - Additional $500 if increasing MW size by more than 20% or changing registration type.\n   - Generator registration fees:\n     - $2,300 for Settlement Only Distribution Generators (SODGs).\n     - $8,000 for generators under 10 MW.\n     - $14,000 for generators 10 MW or greater.\n   - $8,000 for changing an existing SODG to a Distribution Generation Resource (DGR).\n\nThe document provides specific fee amounts and conditions for various registration and modification scenarios.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_2.jpg",
          "page_num": 2,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d7783ee7-2bbe-4d06-a8a7-4e9b8bde0c07",
        "score": 0.66051865,
        "text": "The document is an application form for registering as a Congestion Revenue Right (CRR) Account Holder with the Electric Reliability Council of Texas Inc. (ERCOT). It outlines the process and requirements for approval in accordance with ERCOT Protocols. Applicants must submit a completed application via email and pay a $500 application fee and a $350 background check fee per principal via Electronic Funds Transfer (EFT). Each principal must undergo a background check. The application must include the applicant's name and Data Universal Numbering System (DUNS) number. An Authorized Representative (AR) and an optional Backup AR must be designated, with their contact information provided. The form must be signed by an authorized representative of the company.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols_Section_23_Form_A:_Congestion_Revenue_Right_(CRR)_Account_Holder_Application_for_Registration/page_2.jpg",
          "page_num": 2,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols Section 23 Form A: Congestion Revenue Right (CRR) Account Holder Application for Registration",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d1db4316-6cd7-4f00-aa3a-acaf1c0c62a1",
        "score": 0.64512956,
        "text": "The document is a fee schedule from ERCOT effective October 1, 2024. It outlines various application and inspection fees related to energy generation and transmission services. Key points include:\n\n1. **Full Interconnection Study (FIS) Application Fee**: \n   - $3,000 for new generators.\n   - $2,700 for modifications to existing generators.\n\n2. **Qualified Scheduling Entity (QSE) and Related Fees**:\n   - $500 per entity for QSE, Sub-QSE, Competitive Retailer (CR), Congestion Revenue Right (CRR) Account Holder, Independent Market Information System Registered Entity (IMRE), Resource Entity, and Transmission/Distribution Service Providers (TDSPs).\n\n3. **Counter-Party Background Check Fee**:\n   - $350 per principal.\n\n4. **Weatherization Inspection Fees**:\n   - Resource Entities and Transmission Service Providers must pay fees for weatherization inspections as per Texas Administrative Code \u00a7 25.55.\n\nThe document specifies that fees are associated with modifications based on the cumulative megawatt (MW) amount of changes submitted within the last 12 months. If modifications are less than 10 MW, the fee is $2,300; if 10 MW or greater, the fee is $14,000.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_3.jpg",
          "page_num": 3,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "5db85b18-d957-4966-905b-4bc8062d53b4",
        "score": 0.64487034,
        "text": "The document page outlines specific fees related to ERCOT services:\n\n1. **Requests**: If a request requires ERCOT employee or contractor time, an estimate of labor costs will be provided. The requestor must approve and pay these costs before receiving the information.\n\n2. **ERCOT Training Fees**: Courses that award Continuing Education Hours (CEHs) cost $25 per North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) CEH. Examples include the Operator Training Seminar and Black Start Training.\n\n3. **Cybersecurity Monitor Fee**: This fee for non-ERCOT utilities participating in the Texas Cybersecurity Monitor Program varies annually. The current fee is available on ERCOT's website.\n\nThe document is part of the ERCOT Fee Schedule effective October 1, 2024.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Fee_Schedule/page_5.jpg",
          "page_num": 5,
          "title": "ERCOT Fee Schedule",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c9f4953b-d4cf-427b-90b5-fb5e568953d6",
        "score": 0.6269471,
        "text": "The document is a page from the 2002 Annual Report of the Market Oversight Division, focusing on the ERCOT Administration Fee and Uplift Costs. It includes a table detailing monthly costs from July 2001 to December 2002, with categories such as Balancing Energy Neutrality Adjustment, Black Start Capacity Charge, and others, culminating in a total of $396,027,458.\n\nThe text discusses \"Congestion Rights,\" which began in February 2002. These rights are financial instruments allowing market participants to hedge against congestion costs. The document explains the allocation and auctioning of Transmission Congestion Rights (TCRs) and Pre-assigned Congestion Rights (PCRs), noting that 60% of TCRs are awarded annually and 40% monthly. The total TCR auction revenue was $91.1 million, with credit payments of $22.5 million, resulting in a net revenue of $68.7 million.\n\nThe section on \"Market Issues\" addresses overscheduling and BENA (Balancing Energy Neutrality Adjustment). It highlights how the costs for relieving zonal congestion were distributed among market participants, incentivizing them to schedule generation across congested areas to receive higher payments.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2002/page_12.jpg",
          "page_num": 12,
          "title": "2002 Annual Report on The ERCOT Wholesale Market",
          "year": 2002,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2e52d02d-4402-4591-ae8e-26dc77a5220f",
        "score": 0.6194706,
        "text": "The document is an application form for registration as a Resource Entity with the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT). It outlines the process and requirements for approval in accordance with ERCOT Protocols. Applicants must submit a completed application via email in PDF format and pay a $500 application fee through Electronic Funds Transfer (EFT). The application must be signed by an Authorized Representative or an Officer of the company. ERCOT may request additional information to support operations.\n\nThe form includes sections for:\n\n1. **Entity Information**: \n   - Legal name and address of the applicant.\n   - DUNS Number.\n\n2. **Authorized Representative (AR)**:\n   - Contact details for the AR, who is defined in Section 2.1 of the document.\n\n3. **Backup AR (Optional)**:\n   - Contact details for a backup representative who can act if the AR is unavailable.\n\nFor assistance, a contact number is provided.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols/page_7.jpg",
          "page_num": 7,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "211cd9ff-4921-4196-b713-60c9d6ab3092",
        "score": 0.61079895,
        "text": "The document is an application form for registration as an Independent Market Information System Registered Entity (IMRE) with the Electric Reliability Council of Texas Inc. (ERCOT). It outlines the process for approval in accordance with ERCOT Protocols. Applicants can submit the form electronically and must pay a $500 application fee via Electronic Funds Transfer (EFT) or Automated Clearing House (ACH). The payment should reference the applicant's name and Data Universal Numbering System (DUNS) Number. The form requires the signature of an Authorized Representative or an Officer of the company. ERCOT may request additional information to support operations.\n\nThe form includes sections for:\n\n1. **Entity Information**: \n   - Legal Name and Address of the Applicant\n   - DUNS Number\n\n2. **Authorized Representative (AR)**: \n   - Name, Telephone, and Email Address\n\n3. **Backup Authorized Representative (Optional)**: \n   - Name, Telephone, and Email Address\n\nContact information for assistance is provided, and the document is part of the ERCOT Nodal Protocols effective May 1, 2024.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols/page_2.jpg",
          "page_num": 2,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "053fa2ca-d2c1-45b6-81d8-5697777eb760",
        "score": 0.60521424,
        "text": "The document outlines the ERCOT System Administration and User Fees as part of the settlement and billing process.\n\n### ERCOT System Administration Fee\n1. **Authorization and Purpose**: The Public Utility Commission of Texas (PUCT) authorizes ERCOT to charge this fee to fund its budget. The fee is converted into a charge for each Qualified Scheduling Entity (QSE) using a specified formula.\n   \n2. **Posting and Approval**: ERCOT must post the fee on its website. Any changes approved by PUCT must be posted within two business days, including the effective date.\n\n3. **Calculation**: Each QSE pays the fee for every 15-minute Settlement Interval. The formula provided is:\n   \\[\n   \\text{ESACAMT}_q = \\text{LAFF} \\times \\max(0, \\sum \\text{RTAML}_{q,p})\n   \\]\n   - **ESACAMT\\(_q\\)**: The fee for each QSE per interval.\n   - **RTAML\\(_{q,p}\\)**: Real-Time Adjusted Metered Load for each Settlement Point.\n   - **LAFF**: Load Administration Fee Factor.\n   - **q**: A QSE.\n   - **p**: A Settlement Point.\n\n### User Fees\n1. **Approval and Application**: The ERCOT Board approves user fees for services provided to Market Participants or other entities. These fees are set according to Board Policies and Procedures and may include costs for applications, WAN, and interconnection studies.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_9:_Settlement_and_Billing/page_51.jpg",
          "page_num": 51,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 9: Settlement and Billing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "678cbf77-3c6a-4e57-8b25-7a45bb52b88e",
        "score": 0.6003053,
        "text": "The document page is from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically Section 7 on Congestion Revenue Rights. It outlines definitions and payment protocols related to energy resources and settlements.\n\n1. **Definitions and Variables:**\n   - **RMR Resource:** Defined as the RMR contract price Energy Offer Curve at High Sustained Limit (HSL).\n   - **CLR and ESR:** New items to be implemented, with CLR equating to SWCAP and ESR set at $100/MWh.\n   - **MAXRESP and MAXRESPRK:** Maximum Resource Prices for sources and resources at specific settlement points.\n   - **r and k:** Represent a generation resource and a sink settlement point, respectively.\n\n2. **Payments for FGRs Settled in DAM:**\n   - Currently, there are no defined flowgates.\n\n3. **Payments and Charges for PTP Obligations with Refund Settled in DAM:**\n   - ERCOT will pay the owner of a PTP Obligation with Refund the difference in Day-Ahead Settlement Point Prices between the sink and source Settlement Points, subject to a refund charge if the price difference is positive.\n\nThe document includes placeholders for future system implementations and adjustments to definitions upon implementation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_7_-_Congestion_Revenue_Rights/page_56.jpg",
          "page_num": 56,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 7 - Congestion Revenue Rights",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8df122c9-2592-4ac8-bd57-6054c0dfab95",
        "score": 0.59839773,
        "text": "The document page is from the ERCOT Nodal Protocols, specifically Section 16, which deals with the registration and qualification of market participants. It outlines various charges and payments related to the ERCOT market operations. Key points include:\n\n1. **Charges and Payments**:\n   - Sections (m) to (q) list various charges and payments, such as the ERCOT Contingency Reserve Service Charge and payments for Point-to-Point (PTP) obligations and options settled in the Day-Ahead Market (DAM).\n\n2. **Real-Time Liability Estimate (RTL)**:\n   - ERCOT estimates RTL for an operating day by summing estimates for Real-Time Market (RTM) settlement charges and payments.\n   - Section 6.6.3.1 involves Real-Time Energy Imbalance Payments or Charges at a Resource Node using Real-Time Metered Generation (RTMG).\n   - Section 6.6.3.2 involves payments or charges at a Load Zone using Load Resource Service (LRS) estimates.\n\n3. **Proposed Revisions**:\n   - NPRR1188 and NPRR829 propose changes to sections 6.6.3.1 and 6.6.3.2, respectively, to include additional considerations for generation estimates and telemetry.\n   - Section 6.6.3.3 and 6.6.3.4 cover payments or charges at a Hub and for DC Tie Imports.\n   - Section 6.6.3.8 involves payments or charges for energy from Settlement Only Generators, with proposed revisions by NPRR995 and NPRR1077.\n\nThese sections are part of the broader framework for managing and settling energy transactions in the ERCOT market.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/protocol/ERCOT_Nodal_Protocols:_Section_16:_Registration_and_Qualification_of_Market_Participants/page_59.jpg",
          "page_num": 59,
          "title": "ERCOT Nodal Protocols: Section 16: Registration and Qualification of Market Participants",
          "year": "",
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

